This course provides an overview of the main factors regulating human cognitive and behavioural processes in the context of sport and physical activity. Main issues of cognitive psychology (attention, memory and learning, thinking, language), individual differences (intelligence; personality), developmental processes (cognitive and social development), bases of social behaviour (social cognition and social behaviour), and main topics of clinical psychology (abnormal psychology) are focused on. Aspects important for understanding the initiation and regulation of human movement are accentuated.Objectives/eesmärkid:  This course provides students with knowledge and understanding of psychological responses and adaptations to sport and exercise. Students acquire knowledge and understanding of psychological processes related to both athletic performance and exercise adherence. Lectures and practical training provide forums for understanding and discussion of cognitions, affect and behaviour and the complex interactions between these in sport and exercise settings.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  On completion, students should be able to: (a) show awareness of, and describe a wide range of topics covered by sport and exercise psychology (b) demonstrate basic understanding of research methods and design in sport and exercise psychology (c) demonstrate understanding of theoretical foundation of the psychological processes that influence human performance in athletic settings (d) distinguish the influences that selected psychological factors have on participation in exercise  (e) demonstrate understanding of how sport and exercise behavior influence mental health and well-being  (f) explain the developmental psychological processes that have a special relevance to youth sports and physical  activity (g) describe the influences of social aspects on athletic performance and exercise participation (h) define and distinguish a variety of dysfunctional human behaviors in the context of sport and exercise behavior
